 This not only proves the widespread theory that at least some dinosaurs had feathers, but also provides more details than fossils, such as color and three-dimensional placement.
 According to scientists, the feathers of this animal were brown with a pale or carotenoid underside.
 The discovery also provides insight into the evolution of feathers in birds.
 The researchers concluded that the rachis was probably a later evolutionary development, because dinosaur feathers do not have a well-developed shaft, or rachis, but have other features of feathers - such as barbs.
 The structure of the feathers seems to indicate that they were not used for flying, but to regulate temperature or for display. The researchers suggested that this is the tail of a young dinosaur, but that this monster shows adult feathers and therefore not the down of a chick.
 The researchers suggested that, despite being the tail of a young dinosaur, the monster had the plumage of an adult and not the down of a chick.
