 The entrances to the cave were called 'The Seven Sisters' and all have a diameter of at least 100 to 250 meters.
 Infrared images show that the temperature at night and during the day differs and show that they are probably caves.
 During the day they are cooler than the surrounding surface and at night they are warmer.
 "The thermal behavior of these is not as stable as that of large caves on Earth, which often maintain a temperature that is quite constant," said Glen Cushing of the United States Geological Survey (USGS) Astrogeology Team and Northern Arizona University in Flagstaff, Arizona.
 In France, voting has traditionally required little technology: voters go into a booth and put a pre-printed piece of paper into an envelope marked with the name of the candidate they are voting for.
 Officials first check the voter's identity, then the voter slides the envelope into the ballot box and then puts his or her signature on the voting roll.
 The process is relatively well defined in the French electoral law.
 Ballot boxes have been required to be transparent since 1988, so that both voters and observers can see that there are no envelopes in the box at the start of the election, and that no other envelopes are added than those of registered and authorized voters.
 The candidates can send representatives to witness every part of the process, and volunteers count the votes in the evening under strict supervision and according to specific procedures.
