 There are medium-sized cats that eat medium-sized prey, from hares to antelopes and deer.
 In addition, there are many small cats (such as stray cats kept as pets) that hunt in larger numbers on small prey, such as insects, rodents, lizards and birds.
 Their success comes from the idea of a niche, a special job that each cat has, so that they do not compete with others.
 Lions are the most social cats and live in large groups called prides.
 Troops consist of one to three adult males who are related to each other and have up to thirty females and cubs.
 The women are normally closely related to each other and form a large family of sisters and daughters.
 A pride of lions behaves much like a pack of wolves or dogs, animals that surprisingly resemble lions (but not other big cats) and are very deadly to their prey.
 The tiger is a versatile athlete and can climb (although not well), swim, jump great distances and has five times the pulling power of a strong person.
 The tiger belongs to the same group (Genus Panthera) as lions, leopards and jaguars. These four cats are the only ones that can roar.
 A tiger does not roar with full force like a lion. It is more like he growls a whole sentence.
 Ocelots' favorite meal is small animals. They catch monkeys, snakes, rodents and birds if they can. The ocelot hunts almost exclusively on animals that are much smaller than it is.
 Scholars suspect that ocelots use their sense of smell to hunt small animals (their prey), by sniffing the ground where they have been.
 They can see very well in the dark and move very stealthily. Ocelots hunt by blending in with their surroundings and then pouncing on their prey.
 When a small group of organisms (a small population) breaks away from the large population from which they originated (for example, by moving over a mountain range or river, or if they are moved to an island from which they cannot easily return), they are often in a different environment than before.
 In this new environment, other raw materials and other enemies appear, so the new population must adapt or adapt to be able to face the competition.
 Because they still need the same adaptations as before, the original population has not changed at all.
 As the new population began to adapt to the new environment, they also began to look less and less like the other population.
 After thousands or even millions of years, the two populations will be so different in appearance that you can no longer call them the same species.
 This process is called speciation and simply means the formation of new species. Speciation is an unavoidable consequence and a very important part of evolution.
 Plants produce oxygen that humans breathe and absorb carbon dioxide that humans exhale.
 Through photosynthesis, plants get their nutrients from the sun, and they also provide shade.
 Our houses and clothes are made of plants. We eat mostly plants. Without plants, animals would not survive.
 The Mosasaurus was at the top of the food chain at that time, and had nothing to fear except other Mosasauruses.
 His long jaws had more than 70 razor-sharp teeth, plus an extra set in the mouth, which meant that nothing or no one could escape him.
 It is not certain, but it is possible that his tongue was forked. It ate turtles, large fish, other mosasaurs, and possibly even its own kind.
 In water ponds, nothing was safe from his attacks; even giant dinosaurs like the Tyrannosaurus Rex were no match for him.
