 Meals from Roman times do not contain food that came from America or Asia to Europe in later centuries.
 For example, they did not have corn, tomatoes, potatoes, cacao. In addition, no ancient Roman ever ate a turkey.
 The Babylonians made a primary temple for all their gods. This temple was seen as the god's own house.
 People made offerings to the gods and the priests tried to meet the needs of the gods by organizing ceremonies and festivals.
 Each temple had a public courtyard and a back room that was only accessible to priests.
 Sometimes as part of the temples towers were built in the form of pyramids, called ziggoeratten.
 The top of the tower was a special sanctuary for the god.
