 In 1976, thirty percent of Machu Picchu had been restored. The renovation is still ongoing.
 For example, the most common photo format for still images worldwide is 35 mm, which was the usual film format at the end of the analogue film era.
 These are still produced today, although it is the ratio of the image that the digital camera's image sensor has adopted.
 Oddly enough, 35 mm film is actually 36 mm wide, with a height of 24 mm.
 The aspect ratio of this size (divide by twelve to get the simplest ratio of whole numbers) would be 3:2.
 Many common formats (such as APS-like formats) are equal to or a close approximation of this aspect ratio.
 The rule of thirds, which is often misused and ridiculed by many, is a simple guideline that makes the image dynamic, yet also clear.
 The most effective place for the main subject is at the intersection of the lines. This divides the image vertically and horizontally into three parts (see example).
