 The period in which this happened is commonly referred to as the High Middle Ages, the European history of the 11th, 12th and 13th centuries (1000-1300 AD).
 After the early Middle Ages came the High Middle Ages, which were followed by the Late Middle Ages, which usually end around 1500.
 Technological determinism is a term for a large assortment of ideas in practice: from technological supply or technological compulsion to a strict sense that human destiny is driven by an underlying logic linked to scientific laws and their appearance in technology.
 Most interpretations of technological determinism have these two general views: the development of technology follows a trajectory that largely exceeds cultural or political influence, and that technology in turn has 'effects' on societies that are inherent rather than socially conditioned.
 For example, some will say that the arrival of the car automatically leads to the construction of roads.
 A national road network is not economically feasible for only a few cars, so new production methods are being developed to reduce the cost of car ownership.
 The mass ownership of cars also leads to more accidents on the road and this leads to the development of new techniques in the field of health care to repair the human body.
 In Romanticism, a large part of cultural determinism was included, which came from writers such as Goethe, Fichte and Schlegel.
 In Romanticism, geography formed the individual and over time, customs and cultures emerged from this geography, which formed a harmonious society and were better than the arbitrary imposed laws.
 Constantinople was considered the fashion capital of feudal Europe, as Paris is today.
 It was known as an epicenter of luxury from about 400 AD to about 1100 AD.
 The status of the empire declined in the 12th century, mainly because the crusaders returned with silk and spices that were more valuable than what the Byzantine markets could offer.
 Around this time, Paris also took over the title of fashion capital from Constantinople.
 The Gothic period was at its height in the 10th, 11th and 14th centuries.
 Clothing was initially strongly influenced by Byzantine culture from the east.
 Due to the slow communication channels, however, styles in the West were 25 to 30 years behind.
 At the end of the Middle Ages, a distinctive style began to develop in Western Europe. One of the greatest developments was the result of the Crusades: people began using knots to fasten their clothing.
 Self-sufficient agriculture is agriculture that produces enough food to meet the needs of the farmer and his family.
 Agriculture for subsistence is a simple system that is usually organic, using stored seed from the ecoregion, combined with rotating crops or other relatively simple techniques to maximize yield.
 In the past, most farmers worked in subsistence agriculture. In many developing countries, this is still the case.
 Subcultures bring together like-minded people who feel neglected by societal norms, giving them the opportunity to develop a sense of identity.
 Subcultures can be distinguished by age, ethnicity, social class, location, and/or gender of their members.
 A subculture can be defined by the following types of qualities: linguistic, aesthetic, religious, political, sexual, geographical, or one or more of these factors together.
 Members of a subculture often show which group they belong to by a certain symbolic style in what they wear, in how they behave and the jargon they speak.
 One of the most used methods to illustrate the importance of socialization was the few unfortunate cases of children who, due to neglect, misfortune or deliberate abuse, were not socialized by adults during their growth.
 They are called 'wolf children' or 'wild children'. Some wolf children were locked up by people (usually their own parents); sometimes the child was abandoned because the parents did not want to accept the serious mental or physical disability of the child.
 Troublesome children may have experienced severe child abuse or a serious trauma before they were abandoned or ran away.
 Others have been claimed to have been raised by animals, and some have been said to have lived in the wild only.
 A feral child who has not been raised by humans may display behavior that resembles the behavior of the animal that raised the child (within the physical limits), such as fear of or indifference to humans.
 Learning on a project basis should simplify education and make it more interesting, but scaffolding goes one step further.
 Scaffolding is not a learning method but a tool to support individuals who are faced with a new learning experience, for example a new computer program or who are starting a new project.
 Support can be both virtual and real. A teacher is a form of support, but the paperclipmannetje of Microsoft Office is that too.
 There is virtual scaffolding built into the software that asks questions, provides memory aids and explains procedures that may be difficult to understand without help for students.
 There are several reasons that children end up in foster care, such as neglect, abuse and exploitation.
 No child should grow up in an environment where they are not well cared for, where they are not loved and where they cannot develop, but this is what happens.
 We consider the foster care system to be a safe zone for these children.
 The foster care system is supposed to provide a safe home, loving caregivers, stable education, and reliable health care.
 Foster care must meet all the needs that were neglected in the earlier home.
 The internet combines elements of interpersonal and mass communication.
 The different characters of the internet lead to new dimensions in the application of the Uses & Gratifications-theory.
 'Learning' and 'socialisation' are, for example, presented as important reasons for using the Internet (James et al., 1995).
 Eighmey and McCord (1998) introduced new motivation aspects such as 'personal involvement' and 'continuing relationships' when they investigated audience reactions to Web sites.
 The use of video recordings has led to remarkable discoveries in the interpretation of micro-expressions, which are facial movements that last a few milliseconds.
 It is argued that no one can recognize a lie by only looking at micro-expressions.
 Oliver Sacks described in his essay The President's Speech how people who cannot understand speech because of brain damage can nevertheless accurately judge its sincerity.
 He even suggested that other animal species, such as domestic dogs, also have the ability to interpret human behavior.
 Research in the twentieth century has shown that there are two groups of genetic variants: hidden and visible.
 Mutation adds new genetic variation; selection eliminates this variation from the pool of expressed variation.
 For each generation, there is variation between the two groups by means of separation and recombination.
 A primate with a digestive system similar to that of humans can survive in the savannah, but it is difficult to obtain the necessary amino acids from the plant sources that are available there.
 Furthermore, failure to comply can have serious consequences: stunted growth, malnutrition and even death.
 The easiest plant sources to find are the proteins in leaves and legumes, but unless they are cooked, they are difficult to digest for primates like us.
 Not only is animal food (ants, termites, eggs) easily digestible, but it also contains a lot of proteins that contain all essential amino acids.
 All in all, we should not be surprised if our ancestors solved their 'protein problem' in the same way as chimpanzees solve this problem in the savannah today.
 Sleep disturbance means that you wake up for a reason during your normal sleep period and that you fall asleep again within a short time (10–60 minutes).
 This is quite easy to do by using a relatively soft alarm clock that brings you back to your consciousness without waking you up completely.
 If you set your alarm clock in your sleep, you can place it on the other side of the room so that you have to get out of bed to turn it off.
 Other options based on the biorhythm are, for example, drinking a lot of liquid before going to sleep (and then especially water or tea, a well-known diuretic). This means you have to get up to go to the bathroom.
