 The former allies stood two years after the end of the war opposite each other, this was the beginning of the Cold War.
 The war would last 40 years and proxy armies fought on battlefields in Africa, Asia, Afghanistan, Cuba and many other places.
 The Polish defensive forces held out until 17 September 1939, when they were forced to retreat and reorganize along the bridgehead in Romania.
 These plans were however overtaken in one night, when 800,000 soldiers from the Red Army of the Soviet Union invaded the Latvian and Ukrainian frontiers, after they occupied the eastern parts of Poland, in violation of the Riga Peace Treaty, the Soviet-Polish Non-Aggression Pact and other international peace treaties, both bilateral and multilateral.
 Shipping goods by ship is the most efficient way to transport large numbers of people and goods across the ocean.
 Traditionally, the task of the navy is to ensure that a country retains the ability to transport people and goods, while the ability of the enemy to transport people and goods is impeded.
 The U.S. tried to get troops and equipment across the Atlantic to the British and this North Atlantic campaign of WWII is one of the most remarkable recent examples.
 The German Navy tried to stop this traffic at the same time with the help of mainly U-boats.
 Like the rest of Europe, Britain would probably have been in German hands if the Allies had failed.
 It seems that the goats were first domesticated about 10,000 years ago in the Zagros Mountains of Iran.
 In ancient times, cultures and tribes began to keep them so that they could always get their hair, meat, milk and skins.
 Domesticated goats were usually kept in herds on a hill or other grazing area, and were guarded by a goatherd, often a child or younger person, much like the more familiar shepherd. Today, the same method is still used.
 Already in the 16th century horse railways were built in England.
 Although horse railways consisted of only a rail of planks, the horses had to run faster and pull larger loads than on the somewhat difficult roads of that time.
 Cross-ties were used fairly early to keep the rails in place, but it was gradually realized that rails would be more efficient if there was an iron point on the top.
 This soon became the common practice, but the iron resulted in more wear on the wooden carriage wheels.
 Iron wheels eventually replaced wooden ones. In 1767, the first fully iron rails were laid.
 The first form of transport we know is walking. People started to walk upright two million years ago when the Homo Erectus came up (that means upright man).
 Their predecessor, Australopithecus, walked upright less often.
 Fossils of the Australopithecus from 4.2-3.9 million years ago show bipedal specializations. The Sahelanthropus may have walked on two legs as early as seven million years ago.
