 In many cases, it is like treating the symptoms. But if we want more than a temporary solution, we must identify the cause of the problems and eliminate it.
 The scientific and technological development of human society has obviously changed the earth dramatically. In addition, overpopulation and extravagant human lifestyle have aggravated the problems.
 After the Declaration of Independence was adopted on July 4, 1776, a handwritten copy was sent to the printer John Dunlap a few blocks away. This copy was signed by the President of the Continental Congress, John Hancock, and Secretary Charles Thomson.
 Between 150 and 200 copies were made during the night, and are now better known as 'Dunlap broadsides'.
 John Nixon first delivered the public reading of the document on July 8 in the garden of Independence Hall.
 One copy was sent to George Washington on July 6 and read to his troops in New York on July 9, and another copy arrived in London on August 10.
 The 25 Dunlap broadsides are the oldest surviving copies of the document; the original handwritten copy has not survived.
