 The modern city of Casablanca was founded in the 10th century BC by Berber fishermen, and was used as a strategic port by the Phoenicians, Romans and Merinides, and was known as Anfa.
 The Portuguese destroyed the harbour and rebuilt it under the name Casa Branca. After an earthquake in 1755 they left the city again.
 The Sultan of Morocco rebuilt the city and named it Daru l-Bayad. The Spanish traders who settled here gave it the name Casablanca.
 In Morocco, Casablanca is one of the least interesting places to shop.
 Around the old Medina you will find many places where you can buy traditional Moroccan goods, such as tagines, pots, leather products, water pipes and other trinkets, but it is purely aimed at tourists.
 Goma is a tourist city in the Democratic Republic of Congo. The city is located near Rwanda, in the extreme east.
 In 2002, Goma was destroyed when the Nyiragongo volcano erupted, burying most of the city's streets, and especially the city center.
 Although Goma itself is relatively safe, you should check the situation with regard to the fighting that is going on in the province of North Kivu before visiting outside Goma.
 In addition, the city is the base for climbing the Nyiragongo volcano and you can find some of the cheapest trips for Mountain Gorilla tracking in Africa.
 With boda-boda (a motorcycle taxi) you can move around Goma. The normal (local) price is about 500 Congolese Francs for the short ride.
 Timbuktu is relatively inaccessible and is nowadays used as a metaphor for exotic, distant lands.
 Today, Timbuktu is a dilapidated city, although its reputation makes it a tourist attraction and it has an airport.
 In 1990, it was added to the list of endangered World Heritage Sites because of desert storms.
 It was one of the main stops on the PBS exhibit, Special Wonders from the African World, by Henry Louis Gates.
