 The official currency of the Falkland Islands is the Falkland Islands pound (FKP). The value is approximately one British pound (GBP).
 There is only one bank on the islands, in Stanley opposite the FIC West shop, where you can exchange money.
 In general, British pounds are accepted everywhere on the islands and in Stanley you can also often pay with credit cards and US dollars.
 You probably can't pay with a credit card on the remote islands, but you can probably pay with British and American currency. Ask the owners in advance about how you can pay.
 Exchange your money again before you leave the islands, because Falkland Islands currency is very difficult to exchange outside.
 Montevideo is below the equator, so when it is summer there, it is winter in the northern hemisphere and vice versa.
 Montevideo is located in the subtropics. In the summer months, temperatures of over +30°C are not uncommon.
 Winter can be deceivingly cold: the temperature almost never goes below zero, but the wind in combination with the humidity makes it feel colder than the thermometer indicates.
 The rainfall level remains approximately the same throughout the year, without recognizable 'wet' and 'dry' periods.
 Many of the animals in the park are used to seeing people, but wild animals are still wild. Therefore, they should not be fed or disturbed.
 Keep at least 100 metres away from bears and wolves, and 25 metres away from all other wild animals.
 Elephants, bison, reindeer, bears and pretty much all other large animals can attack you, no matter how tame they seem.
 Every year, dozens of visitors are injured because they do not keep a proper distance. These animals are large, wild and possibly dangerous, so give them space.
 In addition, you should be aware that odors attract bears and other wildlife, so avoid wearing or cooking odorous foods and keep the campsite clean.
