 Stirrups support the rider's feet and hang down on both sides of the saddle.
 They provide the rider with more stability, but can also cause safety problems because the feet of a rider can get stuck in them.
 If a rider is thrown from a horse but manages to hang on with his foot in the stirrup, he can be dragged along with the horse. To reduce the risk, a number of safety measures have been taken.
 Most riders wear firstly riding boots with a heel and a smooth, fairly narrow sole.
 Some saddles, especially English saddles, have safety bars. These bars can break away from the saddle if the rider falls backwards.
 Cochamó Valley - This is the most popular climbing destination in Chile, and is known as the Yosemite of South America, with many different large granite walls and boulders.
 The mountain peaks offer a breathtaking view. Climbers from all parts of the world are constantly discovering new routes on the rock walls that seem to have an endless potential.
 Winter sports where you go downhill, such as skiing and snowboarding, are very popular. You slide down a snow-covered slope with skis or a snowboard on your feet.
 Skiing is a popular travel activity with many enthusiasts, who are sometimes called 'ski bums', who plan entire vacations around skiing at a particular location.
 Skiing has been around for a very long time: there are cave paintings of skiers that date back to 5000 BC!
 The beginning of the ski sport dates at least from the 17th century and in 1861 the first recreational ski resort in Australia was opened by Norwegians.
 Backpacking with skis: this activity is also called off-piste skiing, skitouring or skihiking.
 It's not exactly the same, but it's similar to alpine skiing or mountain climbing, which is done on steep terrain. You need much sturdier skis and boots for this.
 You can see the ski route as a hiking route.
 In good conditions you can cover greater distances than walking, but it is rare that you can reach the speed of cross-country skiing on paved trails without a heavy backpack.
 Europe is a relatively small continent, but with many independent countries. Normally, travelers between different countries have to apply for multiple visas and passport controls.
 The Schengen area, however, functions in this area almost like a single country.
 As long as you stay in this zone, you can usually cross the border without having to go through passport control again.
 If you have a Schengen visa, you do not need to apply for a visa for each Schengen country separately, which saves time, money and paperwork.
 There is no universal definition that indicates which produced items are antiques. Some tax authorities give goods that are older than 100 years the definition of antiques.
 The definition may vary by location. In North America, for example, the age limit is lower than in Europe.
 It is possible to label handicrafts as antiques, even though they are newer than similar mass-produced goods.
 Reindeer herding is an important form of livelihood for the Sámi, and the culture of trading is also very important for many with other occupations.
 Even traditionally, however, not all Sámi were involved in large-scale reindeer husbandry. They supported themselves with fishing, hunting and such things, and reindeer were mostly used as draft animals.
 Many Sámi work in modern professions today. In Sápmi, the Sámi area, tourism is an important source of income.
 The word 'gypsy' is used primarily by non-Roma, but is also often considered offensive because of associations with negative stereotypes and misperceptions of Roma.
 If there is a travel advisory for the country you are travelling to, this may have consequences for your travel health insurance or your cancellation insurance.
 In addition to the advice of your own government, you can also consult the advice of other governments. However, their advice is aimed at their own citizens.
 For example, Americans in the Middle East may face different situations than Europeans or Arabs.
 Advice includes only a brief summary of the political situation in a single country.
 They often give a fleeting, general and extremely simplistic image in comparison with other, more detailed sources.
 Severe weather is the general term for any dangerous weather phenomenon that can lead to damage, serious social disruption or loss of human life.
 Extreme weather conditions can occur anywhere in the world. There are several types of weather conditions, which vary based on geography, topography and atmospheric conditions.
 The effects and consequences of severe weather are, for example, strong wind, hail, large amounts of precipitation and forest fires, but also thunderstorms, tornadoes, flash floods and hurricanes.
 Snowstorms, ice storms and dust storms are examples of regional and seasonal extreme weather events.
 Travellers are advised to be aware of the risks that severe weather conditions in their surroundings may entail, as these may also affect some travel plans.
 Anyone who wants to visit a country that is considered a war zone should be professionally trained.
 A search on the Internet for 'courses in hostile environments' is likely to produce the address of a local company.
 In a course, all the issues outlined here are usually covered in more detail, usually in combination with practical experience.
 A course normally lasts 2 to 5 days and consists of role-plays, a lot of first aid and occasionally weapons training.
 There are many books and magazines with articles about survival in the wilderness, but there are very few publications about war zones.
 Travellers who have planned a sex change operation abroad should ensure that they have the correct documentation for their return journey.
 It varies widely whether governments want to issue passports without gender (X) or to correct a name or gender on documents.
 There is just as much difference in the willingness of foreign governments to recognize these documents.
 Searches at security checks have also become much more extensive since 11 September 2001.
 Transgender individuals who have not yet undergone surgery can assume that they will not come out of this scan with intact privacy and dignity.
 Mudflows are the recurring flow of waves that break on a reef or something similar and flow onto the beach.
 Due to the underwater topography, the return flow is located in some deeper parts, where a rapid flow to deep water can occur.
 Most deaths are caused by exhaustion from trying to swim against the current, which may be impossible.
 When you have escaped from the strong current, swimming back is a piece of cake.
 Try to aim for a place where you won't be grabbed again. Depending on your skills and whether you've been noticed, you can also wait for help.
 The shock of returning is worse than the culture shock (you have a lesser 'honeymoon feeling'), it lasts longer, and it can be more intense.
 Travellers who are easily adaptable to new cultures sometimes have difficulty in adapting to their own culture.
 If you have lived abroad and then returned, you have adapted to the new culture and have lost some of your own customs.
 When you used to go abroad, you noticed that people were patient and understanding. They understood that travelers had to adjust to a new country.
 Usually, patience and understanding are not expected for travelers returning home.
 For children, the pyramid show with light and sound is one of the most interesting activities in the area.
 You see the pyramids in the dark and you see them in silence before the show starts.
 Often, the sound of vendors and tourists can be heard here. The story of the light and sound is like that of a book.
 The Sphinx forms the background and is the narrator of a long story.
 The scenes appear as a projection on the pyramids and the rest of the pyramids is illuminated.
 The South Shetland Islands were discovered in 1819 and have since been claimed by several countries, with the most bases, sixteen active in 2020.
 The archipelago is located 120 km north of the peninsula. The largest island is King George Island with the settlement Villa Las Estrellas.
 Others are Livingston Island, and Deception. Here you will find the overflowing crater of an active volcano that serves as a spectacular natural harbor.
 Ellsworth lies on the southern side of the peninsula, near the border with Bellingshausen Sea.
 Here the mountains of the peninsula turn into the plateau, after which they reappear to form the 360 km long Mount Ellsworth mountain range, which is crossed by the Minnesota Glacier.
 The northern part, also known as the Sentinel Range, includes the highest mountains of Antarctica, the Vinson Massif. Mount Vinson is the highest peak at 4,892 metres (16,050 ft).
 A satellite phone may be your only option in remote locations where there is no cell phone reception.
 A satellite phone is not really a replacement for a mobile phone, since you have to be outside with a clear view of the satellite in order to make a phone call.
 This service is often used by the shipping industry, including pleasure craft, and for expeditions where there is a need for external data and communication.
 Your local telephone provider can give you more information about how to connect to this service.
 It is becoming increasingly popular for people planning a gap year to travel and learn.
 In particular, school leavers make use of this to take a gap year before university without any adverse effects on their studies.
 Often, enrolling in a course abroad during a gap year can increase your chances of pursuing higher education in your own country.
 Normally, there is a fee to enroll in these educational programs.
 Finland is a fantastic destination for boating. The 'Land of a thousand lakes' also has thousands of islands, in the lakes and in the archipelagos off the coast.
 A yacht is not necessary for the archipels or lakes.
 The archipels along the coast and the largest lakes are indeed large enough for any yacht, but with smaller boats or even a kayak you get a completely different experience.
 In Finland, so many people sail in their spare time that the ratio of boats to people is one to seven or eight.
 The figure is equal to the figure of Norway, Sweden and New Zealand. Furthermore, it is quite unique (in the Netherlands, for example, the figure is one in forty).
 Most Baltic cruises include a long stay in St Petersburg (Russia).
 You can spend a few full days in the historic town and stay on the ship.
 Since 2009, you do not need a separate visa if you only go ashore on a boat excursion.
 Some cruises include a visit to the German capital Berlin, but as you can see on the map, Berlin is not close to the sea. A visit to the city is not included in the price of the cruise.
 Air travel can be scary for people of all backgrounds and ages, especially if they have never flown before or have had a traumatic experience.
 It is not something to be ashamed of: it is no different than many fears that other people have.
 Knowing how airplanes work can help to dispel fears that come from the unknown or from the fact that you have no control over the airplane.
 Courier companies are paid a generous fee to deliver items quickly. For business documents, purchases or spare parts for a necessary repair, time often plays a very important role.
 Larger companies could use their own aircraft for certain routes, but for other routes and smaller companies it became more difficult.
 If they ship things by air, it can take days for them to be unloaded and cleared by customs on some routes.
 Only checked baggage could be processed faster. According to the rules of airlines, there must be an accompanying passenger and that is you.
 The most obvious way to fly first or business class is to pay for this privilege (or better, have your employer pay for it).
 However, this is not cheap: the rule of thumb is that you pay about four times economy class for business, and about eleven times for first class.
 It is usually not worthwhile to look for discounts for business class or first class tickets on direct flights from A to B.
 Airlines know very well that there is a group of flyers who are willing to pay a lot of money to get somewhere fast and comfortably and the airlines charge accordingly.
 Chişinău is the capital of Moldova. Here the Romanian language is spoken, but the Russian language is also very common.
 As a multi-ethnic republic, Moldova was plagued by an ethnic conflict.
 In 1994, this conflict led to the creation of the self-proclaimed republic of Transnistria in the east of Moldova. This republic has its own government and currency, but is not recognized by the members of the UN.
 Economic ties have been re-established between these two parts of Moldova, despite the failure of political negotiations.
 Orthodox Christianity is the main religion in Moldova.
 Izmir is the second largest city in Turkey with about 3.7 million inhabitants, the largest port after Istanbul and a good traffic hub.
 The once ancient city of Izmir is now a modern, developed and busy commercial centre on a bay and is surrounded by mountains.
 The broad boulevards, the glass buildings and the modern shopping centers covered with red tiles, the 18th-century markets, the old mosques and churches, but yet the city feels more like a Mediterranean, European city than traditional Turkish.
 In the village of Haldarsvík you can enjoy views of the nearby island of Eysturoy, as well as a special church with eight corners.
 On a number of graves near the church are interesting marble sculptures of doves.
 If you have half an hour, you should definitely take a look around this village.
 In the north you will find the easily accessible, romantic and fascinating town of Sintra. Sintra became famous with foreigners after Lord Byron spoke highly of the beautiful monuments there.
 Scotturb bus 403 runs regularly to Sintra, with a stop in Cabo da Roca.
 Also go north and visit the beautiful Shrine of Our Lady of Fatima (a temple complex), where internationally known Marian apparitions have taken place.
 Remember that you are actually just visiting a mass grave, but also a place that has a meaning for a large part of the world population.
 Many men and women who survived their time here are still alive and many of them have loved ones who were murdered or worked to death there, both Jewish and non-Jewish.
 Show respect, solemnity and dignity during your visit. Do not trivialise the Holocaust or Nazism.
 Do not damage the site by marking or graffiti on the buildings.
 The official languages of Barcelona are Catalan and Spanish. About half of the inhabitants prefer Catalan, the vast majority can understand it, and almost everyone speaks Spanish.
 However, most signs are in Catalan, as that is the first official language according to the law.
 In public transport and other facilities Spanish is spoken frequently.
 Ordinary announcements in the metro are only in Catalan, but unscheduled interruptions are done by an automated system in several languages, including French, Arabic, Spanish, English and also in Japanese.
 The inhabitants of Paris are known as selfish, rude and arrogant.
 Although this is usually just an incorrect stereotype, it can't hurt to put your best foot forward in Paris and behave like someone who is "bien élevé" (well-mannered). This will make it a lot easier to explore Paris.
 The hard exterior of the Parisians disappears quickly when you show that you are familiar with their way of doing things.
 The Plitvice Lakes National Park is heavily forested and this forested area consists primarily of beech, spruce and pine, and includes a combination of alpine and Mediterranean flora.
 There are a lot of different plant communities, because of the different microclimates, the different soil types and the varying height differences.
 This area is also the habitat of a very wide range of animal and bird species.
 Rare animals such as the European brown bear, the wolf, the eagle, the owl, the lynx, the wild cat and the hazel grouse can be found, as well as many more common species.
 When women visit a monastery, they are required to wear a skirt to the knee and their shoulders must be covered.
 Most of the time you get a sash cloth as a woman when you arrive unprepared at a monastery, but if you bring your own copy, with nice screaming colors, the monk or nun at the entrance will smile at you.
 On the other hand, men must wear trousers to at least above the knee.
 You can also borrow from the stock at the entrance, but this clothing is not washed after each use, so you may not feel comfortable with that. One size fits all for men!
 Like many other Mediterranean regions, Mallorcan cuisine is based on bread, vegetables and meat (especially pork) and olive oil is used extensively.
 A simple and popular dish for dinner, especially during the summer months, is Pa amb Oli: bread with olive oil, tomatoes and whatever is available to add flavor, such as cheese, tuna, etc.
 Nouns, like Sie, which means you, always have a capital letter at the beginning, even if they are in the middle of the sentence.
 In this way you make a clear distinction between a number of verbs and objects.
 It probably also makes reading easier. However, writing is more complicated, because you have to figure out whether a verb or an adjective should be used as a noun.
 Most Italian words are written exactly as they are pronounced, so the pronunciation generally poses few problems.
 You have to pay attention to the c and the g. The pronunciation of these letters depends on the vowel that follows.
 Also, you have to pronounce the r and rr differently: caro means darling, while carro means car.
 The Persian language has a relatively simple and mostly regular grammar.
 Reading this introduction to the grammar will teach you a lot about the grammar of Persian and help you to understand sentences.
 It is quite logical that if you know a Romance language, it is easier for you to learn Portuguese.
 But people who speak a little Spanish can quickly conclude that Portuguese is so similar that you don't have to learn it separately.
 Pre-modern observatories are now obsolete, and serve as museums or educational attractions.
 Light pollution was not as big of a problem back then, so they were often built in cities or on campuses, more accessible than they are today.
 Most modern research telescopes are enormous facilities built in remote areas with favorable atmospheric conditions.
 Hanami is the viewing of cherry blossoms and has been a part of Japanese culture since the 8th century.
 In China, plum blossoms were the favorite flowers and that is where the concept came from.
 The first cherry blossom festivals in Japan were organized by the emperor and were only intended for himself and other aristocrats at the imperial court.
 Plants look best in a natural environment, which means you have to resist the temptation to remove even just one species.
 When you collect specimens during a visit to a landscaped garden, you are immediately and without discussion denied access to the garden.
 Singapore is generally a very safe place to stay, very easy to navigate and almost everything is available upon arrival.
 But if you are in the 'tropics', but a few degrees to the north of the equator, you experience both heat (always) and strong sun (when the air is clear, this happens less often).
 There are also some buses going north to Hebron, the supposed burial place of the biblical patriarchs Isaac, Jacob, Abraham and their wives.
 Make sure the bus you take is really going to Hebron and not just to the nearby Jewish settlement of Kiryat Arba.
 Inland waterways can be a good holiday destination.
 You can visit castles in the Loire Valley or the Rhine Valley, book a cruise to the interesting cities along the Danube or take a boat trip along the Erika Canal.
 They also give popular hiking and cycling routes.
 Christmas is one of the most important holidays of the Christian faith, celebrating the birth of Jesus.
 People who do not believe in Christian countries and non-Christians around the world have also adopted many traditions associated with the holiday.
 There is a tradition of staying up all night on Easter Eve until you can see the sunrise.
 Of course, there are Christian theological explanations for this tradition, but it may just as well be a pre-Christian spring and fertility ritual.
 In traditional churches, a Easter Vigil is often held on the Saturday evening of the Easter weekend, where the congregation often celebrates the resurrection of Christ at midnight.
 All animals that originally arrived at the islands came by swimming, flying or drifting.
 Due to the long distance from the continent, it was not possible for mammals to make the journey, and as a result the giant tortoise became the most common grazing mammal on the Galapagos Islands.
 Since humans set foot on the Galapagos, all sorts of mammals have been introduced, including goats, horses, cows, rats, cats and dogs.
 During the winter, the Arctic and Antarctic regions experience polar night, which means that the sun does not actually rise.
 There is a good chance you will be able to see the aurora borealis, as the sky will be dark almost all day and night.
 The areas are sparsely populated and therefore light pollution is not often a problem, which means you can enjoy the starry sky.
 The Japanese work environment is more structured and formal than in the Western world.
 Pakken are standard work clothes and colleagues call each other by their last name or job title.
 Unity in the workplace is crucial. The focus is on group performance rather than on the praise of individual work performance.
 Employees often need permission from their supervisors before they can make a decision and are expected to follow the instructions of their supervisors without question.
